    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I saw a note in the manual about blockages being a serious issue though. What kind of things usually clog them up, and how does that actually affect the reading on the instrument?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Pitot tubes are vulnerable to blockages from various substances, such as dirt, sand, bird droppings, or ice. Filament blockages happen as well, formed by condensation and pitot bore compounds. When a blockage occurs, the accurate dynamic pressure measurement slows down, leading to turbulence on the pitot tube and stagnant pressure around it. This improper airflow can dramatically increase the indicated airspeed falsely, risking a stall unless the pilot takes immediate action, like retracting the landing gear to reduce drag. Regular inspections, possibly in the Icing Cold Weather Operations Placard section of maintenance manuals, ensure a clear airflow path.",
      "source": "target",
